327":"1327","1349":"1349","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","1288":"1288","1354":"1354","1342":"1342","1331":"1331","1320":"1320","about 1323":"circa 1323","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","Kempton, West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1308–1350":"1308–1350","1305–1349":"1305–1349","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1327–1363":"1327–1363","1329–Male":"1329–Deceased","1331–1342":"1331–1342","–Female":"Deceased","1272–Female":"1272–Deceased","1323–1377":"1323–1377","1285–1354":"1285–1354","1288–Female":"1288–Deceased","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1272":"1272","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","1288":"1288","1354":"1354","1342":"1342","1331":"1331","1320":"1320","about 1323":"about 1323","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","Kempton, West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Swinburne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Durham): habitational name primarily from Great and Little Swinburne (Northumberland), but perhaps also occasionally from one or other places similarly named, from Old English <i>swīn</i> ‘pig’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George De Swinburne was born in 1308, his father, Sir William Swinburne, was 24 and his mother, Alice de Vaux, was 21. He had at least 1 daughter with Grace Swinburne. He died in 1350, in Manor, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1308–1350":"1308–1350","1305–1349":"1305–1349","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1327–1363":"1327–1363","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1331–1342":"1